tool.name: Ensemble_Model

param.name: in_layers
param.dialogReference:
Takes one or more NetCDF files depicting fuzzy sigmoidal evidence layers created prior in the Ensemble Sigmoider tool. All inputs must have a single 'sigmoid' variable and x and y coordinates in GDA 94 Albers projection (3577).

Each input evidence layer must be assigned as either type belief or disbelief and at least one of each is required for modelling. The belief and disbelief inputs are described:

  • Belief: values closer 1 represent areas you believe your target is highly likely to exist

  • Disbelief: values closer to 1 represent areas you do not believe your target is highly likely to exist

param.name: out_nc
param.dialogReference:
A NetCDF file containing the ensemble model results. Four variables are contained within the output:

  • belief: the combination of all belief (i.e. presence) evidence

  • disbelief: the combination of all disbelief (i.e. absence) evidence

  • plausibility: the combined belief and disbelief evidence showing all possible areas (accurate or not) of the target phenomenon

  • interval: areas where the ensemble model was uncertain based on current evidence data

param.name: in_resample
param.dialogReference: If input pixel resolution varies, set whether to resample all inputs to match the lowest or highest resolution input.

param.name: in_win_size
param.dialogReference:
Smoothing of all input evidence layers prior to ensemble modelling can reduce visual artefacts that may occur from resampling and other input aggregation procedures. The smoothing value must be an odd number between 3 and 99. Higher values apply more smoothing.

Leave this empty to ensure no smoothing is applied.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the results to the currently active map once tool is complete or not.

tool.summary:
Perform Dempster-Shafer belief modelling. This tool takes two or more NetCDF file evidence layers created using Ensemble Sigmoider prior and performs probability-based ensemble modelling. The benefit of this method is that not only can multiple evidence layers be combined statistically, but Dempster-Shafer outputs include additional maps showing areas of model plausibility and uncertainty (i.e., under-sampled areas of the landscape that might need attention).

See citation: https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/dempster-shafer-theory.
